==1型遠端RTA==<!--
{{main|Distal renal tubular acidosis}}
[[File:XrayRicketsLegssmall.jpg|thumb]] of a child with [[rickets|rickets]], a complication of both distal and proximal RTA.]]
Distal RTA ('''dRTA''') is the classical form of RTA, being the first described. Distal RTA is characterized by a failure of acid secretion by the alpha intercalated [[cell_(biology)|cell]]s of the [[medullary_collecting_duct|medullary collecting duct]] of the [[Anatomical_terms_of_location#Proximal_and_distal|distal]] [[nephron|nephron]]. This failure of acid secretion may be due to a number of causes, and it leads to an inability to acidify the urine to a [[pH|pH]] of less than 5.3. Because renal excretion is the primary means of eliminating acid from the body, there is consequently a tendency towards [[acidemia|acidemia]]. There is an inability to excrete {{chem|link=Hydron (chemistry)|H|+}} while {{chem|link=Potassium|K|+}} cannot be reclaimed by the cell, leading to acidemia (as {{chem|H|+}} builds up in the body) and hypokalemia (as {{chem|K|+}} cannot be reabsorbed by the alpha cell).
This leads to the clinical features of dRTA;<ref name=laing/> In other words, the intercalated cells' apical H+/K+ antiporter is non-functional, resulting in proton retention and potassium excretion. Since calcium stones demonstrate a proclivity for deposition at higher pHs (alkaline), the substance of the kidney develops stones bilaterally; this does not occur in the other RTA types.
*Normal [[anion_gap|anion gap]] [[metabolic_acidosis|metabolic acidosis]]/acidemia
*[[Hypokalemia|Hypokalemia]], [[Hypocalcemia|Hypocalcemia]], [[Hyperchloremia|Hyperchloremia]]
*[[kidney_stone|Urinary stone]] formation (related to alkaline urine, [[hypercalciuria|hypercalciuria]], and low urinary citrate).<ref name="Buckalew">{{cite journal
 | author = Buckalew VM Jr
 | title = Nephrolithiasis in renal tubular acidosis
 | journal = [[The_Journal_of_Urology|The Journal of Urology]]
 | volume = 141
 | issue = 3 (part 2)
 | pages = 731–737
 | year = 1989
 | pmid = 2645431}}</ref>
*[[Nephrocalcinosis|Nephrocalcinosis]] (deposition of [[calcium|calcium]] in the substance of the kidney)
*[[Bone|Bone]] demineralisation (causing [[rickets|rickets]] in children and [[osteomalacia|osteomalacia]] in adults)
*[[Sjogren's_syndrome|Sjogren's syndrome]]-->

==2型近端RTA==<!--
{{main|Proximal renal tubular acidosis}}
Proximal RTA ('''pRTA''') is caused by a failure of the [[proximal_tubular|proximal tubular]] cells to reabsorb filtered bicarbonate from the urine, leading to urinary bicarbonate wasting and subsequent acidemia. The distal intercalated cells function normally, so the acidemia is less severe than dRTA and the urine can acidify to a pH of less than 5.3.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Rodriguez Soriano J, Boichis H, Stark H, Edelmann CM |title=Proximal renal tubular acidosis. A defect in bicarbonate reabsorption with normal urinary acidification |journal=Pediatr. Res. |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=81–98 |year=1967 |pmid=6029811 |doi=10.1203/00006450-196703000-00001}}</ref> pRTA also has several causes, and may occasionally be present as a solitary defect, but is usually associated with a more generalized dysfunction of the proximal tubular cells called [[Fanconi_syndrome|Fanconi syndrome]], in which there is also [[phosphaturia|phosphaturia]], [[glycosuria|glycosuria]], aminoaciduria, uricosuria, and tubular [[proteinuria|proteinuria]].

The principal feature of Fanconi syndrome is bone demineralization ([[osteomalacia|osteomalacia]] or [[rickets|rickets]]) due to phosphate wasting.-->

==3型RTA-整合近端和遠端的RTA==<!--
In some patients, RTA shares features of both dRTA and pRTA. This rare pattern was observed in the 1960s and 1970s as a transient phenomenon in infants and children with dRTA (possibly in relation with some exogenous factor such as high salt intake) and is no longer observed.<ref name="jrs">{{cite journal |author=Rodríguez Soriano J |title=Renal tubular acidosis: the clinical entity |journal=J. Am. Soc. Nephrol. |volume=13 |issue=8 |pages=2160–70 |date=August 2002 |pmid=12138150 |url=http://jasn.asnjournals.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=12138150 |doi=10.1097/01.ASN.0000023430.92674.E5}}</ref> This form of RTA has also been referred to as juvenile RTA.<ref>{{cite book |author=de Jong PE, Koomans HA, Weening JJ |title=Klinische Nefrologie |publisher=Elsevier |location=Maarssen |year=2000 |pages=141–2 |edition=3rd}}</ref>

Combined dRTA and pRTA is also observed as the result of inherited [[carbonic_anhydrase|carbonic anhydrase]] II deficiency. Mutations in the gene encoding this enzyme give rise to an autosomal recessive syndrome of [[osteopetrosis|osteopetrosis]], renal tubular acidosis, [[Cerebrum|cerebral]] [[calcification|calcification]], and mental retardation.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Sly WS, Whyte MP, Sundaram V, ''et al.'' |title=Carbonic anhydrase II deficiency in 12 families with the autosomal recessive syndrome of osteopetrosis with renal tubular acidosis and cerebral calcification |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=313 |issue=3 |pages=139–45 |date=July 1985 |pmid=3925334 |doi=10.1056/NEJM198507183130302 |url=http://www.nejm.org/doi/abs/10.1056/NEJM198507183130302?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dpubmed}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Shah GN, Bonapace G, Hu PY, Strisciuglio P, Sly WS |title=Carbonic anhydrase II deficiency syndrome (osteopetrosis with renal tubular acidosis and brain calcification): novel mutations in CA2 identified by direct sequencing expand the opportunity for genotype-phenotype correlation |journal=Hum. Mutat. |volume=24 |issue=3 |pages=272 |date=September 2004 |pmid=15300855 |doi=10.1002/humu.9266 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Pushkin A, Abuladze N, Gross E, ''et al.'' |title=Molecular mechanism of kNBC1-carbonic anhydrase II interaction in proximal tubule cells |journal=J. Physiol. (Lond.) |volume=559 |issue=Pt 1 |pages=55–65 |date=August 2004 |pmid=15218065 |pmc=1665076 |doi=10.1113/jphysiol.2004.065110 |url=http://www.jphysiol.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=15218065}}</ref> It is very rare and cases from all over the world have been reported, of which about 70% are from the [[Magreb|Magreb]] region of North Africa, possibly due to the high prevalence of [[consanguinity|consanguinity]] there.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Fathallah DM, Bejaoui M, Lepaslier D, Chater K, Sly WS, Dellagi K |title=Carbonic anhydrase II (CA II) deficiency in Maghrebian patients: evidence for founder effect and genomic recombination at the CA II locus |journal=Hum. Genet. |volume=99 |issue=5 |pages=634–7 |year=1997 |pmid=9150731 |doi=10.1007/s004390050419 |url=http://www.springerlink.com/content/7fvlgeehvxf5d5rt/fulltext.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>
The kidney problems are treated as described above. There is no treatment for the osteopetrosis or cerebral calcification.

Type 3 is rarely discussed.<ref name=emed>{{EMedicine|article|242494|Hyporeninemic Hypoaldosteronism}}</ref> Most comparisons of RTA are limited to a comparison of types 1, 2, and 4.-->

==4型RTA==<!--
[[File:Aldosterone-2D-skeletal.svg|thumb]], or to a resistance to its effects.]]
Type 4 RTA is not actually a tubular disorder at all nor does it have a clinical syndrome similar to the other types of RTA described above. It was included in the classification of renal tubular acidoses as it is associated with a mild (normal anion gap) metabolic acidosis due to a ''physiological'' reduction in proximal tubular [[ammonium|ammonium]] excretion (impaired ammoniagenesis), which is secondary to [[hypoaldosteronism|hypoaldosteronism]], and results in a decrease in urine buffering capacity. Its cardinal feature is [[hyperkalemia|hyperkalemia]], and measured urinary acidification is normal, hence it is often called hyperkalemic RTA or tubular hyperkalemia.<ref name=emed/> 

Causes include:
*Aldosterone deficiency ([[hypoaldosteronism|hypoaldosteronism]]): Primary vs. hyporeninemic
*[[Aldosterone|Aldosterone]] resistance
